Theorem A.2 (Fact): Let $\bS_1,\cdots,\bS_n\in\RR^{N\times N}$ be independent random matrices such that $\E{\bS_i}=0$ and $\norm{\bS_i}_{\op}\leq L$ almost surely for all $i$. Define $\bZ=\sum_{i=1}^n \bS_n$ and the \emph{matrix variance statistic} $v(\bZ)$ as
\begin{equation*}
\textstyle v(\bZ) = \max\left\{\norm{\E{\bZ\bZ^\top}}_{\op}, \norm{\E{\bZ^\top \bZ}}_{\op}\right\} = \max\left\{\Norm{\sum_{i=1}^n\E{\bS_i\bS_i^\top}}_{\op}, \Norm{\sum_{i=1}^n\E{\bS_i^\top \bS_i}}_{\op} \right\}.
\end{equation*}
Then it holds for all $t>0$ that
